{
  "texts": [
    "This recursive dynamic, by which mediatization foregrounds the possibility of Artificial Sociality, which in turns enhances the depth of mediatization, reflects the fact that deep mediatization is to be understood as a recursive process itself (Hepp, 2020a).",
    "In the last two decades, several researchers and scholars have argued for the need of a paradigm change in AI and robotics from the reproduction of intelligence to \"artificial social intelligence\" (ASI), understood as a new step toward human-like intelligence (Dautenhahn, 2007; Vinciarelli et al., 2009).",
    "As a concept, however, ASI reproduces some of the problems associated with the notion of AI.",
    "Since the origins of AI, in fact, the term intelligence has proved problematic due to the difficulty of clarifying what it means and how it can be applied to nonhuman entities (Moore, 2020).",
    "Similar concerns are also raised by the notion of social intelligence."
  ]
}